<p rend="left">les sinus qui se trouvent 〈sur le〉 trajet de l’air, et, dès lors, les frontaux sont dans ce cas aussi bien que tous ceux qui entourent les fosses nasales; dès lors aussi, par l’écartement des deux lames de l’os, le gonflement des bosses frontales, indépendantes et séparées par un silon—“—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I suppose you have Owen’s British Fossil Mammalia—look to pp 88 &amp; 89 &amp; you will find one or two remarks having reference to DeBlainvilles conclusions—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> It is true what DeB. states—that the frontal sinuses &amp; the facial part of the skull is particularly prone to vary</p>
<p>〈<hi rend="underline">section missing</hi>〉</p>
<p>Geo R Waterhouse</p>
<p>It is not true, in my opinion, that all these Fossil Cave Bears are of one &amp; the same species— there are certainly two very distinct species— The one with the enormous frontal sinuses (U. <hi rend="underline">spelæus</hi>) varies <hi rend="underline">much</hi> in the development of the part in question, but there are characters in the teeth &amp; form of the lower jaw (especially in the condyle) of <hi rend="underline">U. priscus</hi> which make it easy of separation—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note>1.1 les sinus … to vary 2.4] <hi rend="italic">crossed pencil</hi></note>
                <note>4.1 It is … separation— 4.5] ‘Ch. 7’<ref target="#foot.f4"/> <hi rend="italic">brown crayon,</hi> <hi rend="italic">underl brown crayon</hi>; ‘Feb. 1860’ <hi rend="italic">added</hi> <hi rend="italic">pencil</hi></note>
                <note>4.2 The one … in question, 4.4] <hi rend="italic">double scored pencil</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
